Dt44uUaKgY_jVz1L56JxSJQXOvIEMrgxrjhhrM8olrrZWfpLlF36OeyU8z0VvtHhE4ZAMc-P7WW6WbQ-9M101-BGo4KmrWiAz9a-PIkOKBxH0bpBWxzqMTQksdECFv9XTTolFUAl3EdqWIQfo_IpnhbjfWnfhj0ilKcZpDWIKhjO8ZcgshrwdFxzjRrJARBTpT9G7bph3gvi2WTe6mS3yWxXKo1DliqkHC_gB-K90vc8jB0ZwNDcIRlSlWp3yLBzeovnM06rzNYGhC0h3aPliwvSZ3-qP0C02ly26NK_wiy4ygba9crifbxqOMKr0S4ELhjSB-O90kKSBHh-GXq_Z3EAuUi_pd-Q73olp4biu_E4zDxiFJAB_AtLL08FGv7RRJDyLeR9zHm-rB22RqPcjvP6UkXnID-Wz_gHP7gHJCTPc9LL4jiW0RR_H8TClCcqesbeb-Pj-lUip2B1wkFHhjE9coMbrYQ20DDP5wiR1076iAq4uEFXzcuFaIAsH5mHlYNfcXXlDW4byyXFhKguHIkU5Ah4Lczd49K8exDFgcN_L-PApL1fdNobjGgXogXP-VFFDdvFJhuVYSo1WCXPlfq84z_lkEAQUSUmKxkv8XHGUxMxthM2mKkjYMlUdjv33SSJQV9hI3kDMwngYdl4w66cDK03YSz706ftWR7Ro0hTHsFNkRW8lLcncbVzXDhMdHsu_Tk9JvXPvgVPG7b4mdJynS74YBMDkWYR4dTFpx7ui7F1BCVYQj2Hiy7JokdRh_7ALN9DO79ckqZy5ZAqlSjc91s0fWi0v2oMWLXbNyMsZc5Cm5NMyeMzMrlC83NPIad9cEybGsu_nvol4OrPaaHuJetJTgLP3818jTijyg9Y4pQ17Zu8m1n46_mFkRA==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing code requirements**\\n\\nI’m considering several aspects of the code structure with potential issues in the LoggerContextVO and its references, like birthTime and propertyMap. It seems necessary to create an event before starting the thread since the ObjectInputStream is waiting for a header, which might block the thread. I need to ensure thread-safety for the appender list as it’s mutated in the SocketNode thread. There are other details about Checkstyle and tests to think through.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering socket management**\\n\\nI’m evaluating whether to use `serverSocket.bind` for a timeout instead of the constructor because the constructor binds automatically. I realize I may need to clean up if an assertion fails before joining the thread, as that could leave the test hanging with a running background thread. I’ll implement a cleanup process with `closeQuietly` for all sockets and manage the socket node thread appropriately, setting it as a daemon for safety. However, I should consider if a daemon thread is acceptable post-test.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Looking at exception handling**\\n\\nI need to account for potential exceptions that might arise from removing the socket server list in SocketNode. It seems smart to detach or stop the appender in the cleanup process, especially since `context.stop` will close it. I’m also considering whether to use a try-with-resources statement since the accepted socket is assigned after the accept call. While I could use a nested try, it seems simpler to keep the final cleanup straightforward.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating error handling in Java**\\n\\nI'm considering how to handle IOException when coding. The developer advises against using empty catch blocks, which seems sensible since cleanup might require error management and logging. During testing, I could use Closeable and catch IOException as needed. To avoid issues, I’ll need to use try-with-resources for both the ServerSocket and any client connections to streamline resource management. This way, I can ensure proper cleanup without manual intervention, minimizing potential errors.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing socket management in Java**\\n\\nI'm considering the implications if the join timeout assertion fails; it looks like the accepted socket would close due to the try-with block. That's good because it ensures cleanup. However, I might need to be cautious about a thread lingering even after asserting that it's not alive. Also, if the ObjectOutputStream closes the clientSocket's output stream, I have to make sure that the ServerSocket is eventually closed. \\n\\nI’ll have to be mindful of the daemon thread behavior so the tests don't exit too soon, potentially before cleanup finishes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ABpu5E6tuSYAJ8b8Fr7RUVE4|fc_0c940d5797260995016a0580513f4881a2b76a4f11ab94a064", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.5.26/src/test/java/org/graalvm/logback/SocketNodeTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org.graalvm.logback;\n\nimport java.io.ObjectOutputStream;\nimport java.net.InetAddress;\nimport java.net.InetSocketAddress;\nimport java.net.ServerSocket;\nimport java.net.Socket;\n\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.Level;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.Logger;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.LoggerContext;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.net.SimpleSocketServer;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.net.SocketNode;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.spi.ILoggingEvent;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.spi.LoggingEvent;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.spi.LoggingEventVO;\nimport ch.qos.logback.classic.util.LogbackMDCAdapter;\nimport ch.qos.logback.core.read.ListAppender;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class SocketNodeTest {\n\n  private static final int SOCKET_TIMEOUT_MILLIS = 5_000;\n\n  @Test\n  void readsSerializedLoggingEventFromSocket() throws Exception {\n    LoggerContext loggerContext = new LoggerContext();\n    loggerContext.setName(\"socket-node-test\");\n    loggerContext.setMDCAdapter(new LogbackMDCAdapter());\n\n    try {\n      ListAppender<ILoggingEvent> appender = new ListAppender<>();\n      appender.setContext(loggerContext);\n      appender.start();\n\n      Logger remoteLogger = loggerContext.getLogger(\"org.graalvm.logback.SocketNodeTest.remote\");\n      remoteLogger.setAdditive(false);\n      remoteLogger.setLevel(Level.INFO);\n      remoteLogger.addAppender(appender);\n\n      try (ServerSocket serverSocket = new ServerSocket(0, 1, InetAddress.getLoopbackAddress());\n          Socket clientSocket = new Socket()) {\n        serverSocket.setSoTimeout(SOCKET_TIMEOUT_MILLIS);\n        clientSocket.connect(new InetSocketAddress(InetAddress.getLoopbackAddress(), serverSocket.getLocalPort()),\n            SOCKET_TIMEOUT_MILLIS);\n\n        try (Socket acceptedSocket = serverSocket.accept()) {\n          SimpleSocketServer socketServer = new SimpleSocketServer(loggerContext, serverSocket.getLocalPort());\n          SocketNode socketNode = new SocketNode(socketServer, acceptedSocket, loggerContext);\n          Thread socketNodeThread = new Thread(socketNode, \"socket-node-test-reader\");\n          socketNodeThread.setDaemon(true);\n          socketNodeThread.start();\n\n          LoggingEventVO loggingEvent = createLoggingEvent(remoteLogger, \"message from a remote socket\");\n          try (ObjectOutputStream outputStream = new ObjectOutputStream(clientSocket.getOutputStream())) {\n            outputStream.writeObject(loggingEvent);\n            outputStream.flush();\n          }\n\n          socketNodeThread.join(SOCKET_TIMEOUT_MILLIS);\n          assertThat(socketNodeThread).isNotAlive();\n          assertThat(appender.list).hasSize(1);\n          assertThat(appender.list.get(0).getFormattedMessage()).isEqualTo(\"message from a remote socket\");\n        }\n      }\n    } finally {\n      loggerContext.stop();\n    }\n  }\n\n  private static LoggingEventVO createLoggingEvent(Logger logger, String message) {\n    LoggingEvent loggingEvent = new LoggingEvent(SocketNodeTest.class.getName(), logger, Level.INFO, message, null,\n        null);\n    return LoggingEventVO.build(loggingEvent);\n  }\n}\n"}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.5.26/src/test/java/org/graalvm/logback/SocketNodeTest.java\",\"content\":\"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage org.graalvm.logback;\\n\\nimport java.io.ObjectOutputStream;\\nimport java.net.InetAddress;\\nimport java.net.